  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">A care should be taken with this terminology. Rather, as in the general case of creation of particles by an external field, see e.g. [8], we are talking about amplification of vacuum fluctuations of the quantized wavefunction by evolving gravitational field</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">30</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">The fact that the vacuum state is strongly squeezed in a similar model was also note by [16]</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">31</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that often the logarithm of scale factor is denoted as α, see e.g. [6], [18]. However, we prefer to use t for this variable to stress its time-like character</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">32</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that equations describing the evolution of scalar and tensor cosmological perturbations also have the same structure, see e.g. [21] and [20]</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">33</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that in the cosmological context the potential is often defined with the opposite sign</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">34</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">In the classically allowed region the phase S plays the role of classical action characterising a particular classical trajectory of our model. Using this fact, one can show that every component of vector k is proportional to the derivative of corresponding field φi over the physical time</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">35</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">In the course of the calculation we use the well known relation Γ(1 + ix)Γ(1 - ix) = πx sinh(πx)</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">36</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Let us stress the difference between a wavefunction corresponding to a quantum state of our system and the wavefunction of the Universe. The latter plays the role of a generalised coordinate in the formalism of third quantization</subfield>
